Here is a clean, self-contained chain that keeps every equality correct and ends with the desired volume–divergence identity.  (All integrals are assumed finite; \(\rho_0\) is any square–integrable initial density.)

\[
\begin{aligned}
\sum_{i=1}^{n}\lambda_i
&=\lim_{t\to\infty}
      \int_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}
      \frac1{t}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\log\sigma_i\!\bigl(D\Phi_t(x)\bigr)\,
      \rho_0(x)\,dx \\[6pt]
&=\lim_{t\to\infty}
      \int_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}
      \frac1{t}\,\log\det D\Phi_t(x)\,
      \rho_0(x)\,dx \\[6pt]
&=\lim_{t\to\infty}
      \int_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}
      \frac1{t}\int_{0}^{t}
          \operatorname{Tr}\!\bigl(\nabla f\bigl(\Phi_s(x)\bigr)\bigr)\,ds\;
      \rho_0(x)\,dx 
      \quad\;(\text{Jacobi}) \\[6pt]
&=\lim_{t\to\infty}
      \frac1{t}\int_{0}^{t}
          \int_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}
              \operatorname{Tr}\!\bigl(\nabla f(y)\bigr)\,
              \rho_s(y)\,dy\,ds
          \quad\; (y=\Phi_s(x)) \\[6pt]
&=\lim_{t\to\infty}
      \frac1{t}\int_{0}^{t}
          \bigl\langle\nabla\!\cdot f\bigr\rangle_{\rho_s}\,ds .
\end{aligned}
\]

Here \(\rho_s=\Phi_{s\#}\rho_0\) is the density obtained by pushing \(\rho_0\) forward under the flow, and  
\(\langle\nabla\!\cdot f\rangle_{\rho_s}:=\int\nabla\!\cdot f\,\rho_s\).

---

* If the \(\rho_s\) converge to an invariant density \(\rho_\infty\), the average inside the limit stabilises, giving  
  \[
  \sum_{i=1}^{n}\lambda_i
     =\int_{\mathbb{R}^{n}}\nabla\!\cdot f(x)\,\rho_\infty(x)\,dx .
  \]

* If the flow is ergodic with respect to an invariant measure \(\mu\), the inner space–time average collapses (by Birkhoff) to a single trajectory average, yielding the standard pointwise identity  

  \[
  \boxed{\;
     \sum_{i=1}^{n}\lambda_i(x)
       =\lim_{t\to\infty}\frac1{t}
         \int_{0}^{t}\nabla\!\cdot f\bigl(\Phi_s(x)\bigr)\,ds
     \;}
     \quad\text{for }\mu\text{-a.e. }x.
  \]

So the equality between the total Lyapunov exponent and the long-time mean divergence follows directly from Jacobi’s formula plus Oseledets’ limit.

\[
\boxed{\;
\begin{aligned}
\sum_{i=1}^{n}\lambda_i
      &=\lim_{t\to\infty}\frac{1}{t}\log\det D\Phi_t(x)\\[6pt]
      &=\lim_{t\to\infty}\frac{1}{t}\int_{0}^{t}\nabla\!\cdot f\bigl(\Phi_s(x)\bigr)\,ds\\[6pt]
      &=\lim_{t\to\infty}\frac{1}{t}\int_{0}^{t}\int_{\mathbb R^{n}}
                \rho(y,s)\,\nabla\!\cdot f(y)\,dy\,ds\\[6pt]
      &=\lim_{t\to\infty}\frac{1}{t}\int_{0}^{t}
                \dot H(s)\,ds\\[6pt]
      &=\bigl\langle\dot H\bigr\rangle_{\text{time}}
\end{aligned}
\;}
\]

Hence the long-time average differential-entropy production rate equals the sum of the Lyapunov exponents.

